<user>112494219825156497691<//user><Name>Patrick Brooks< /Name><date>1535085228756<//date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
I drove from Redondo Beach to south San Diego to have a key cut and remote programmed at The Key Crew.  On my way there, I received a telephone call to reschedule my visit. I replied that I could not as I was already en route. Their prices were very high but, albeit, lower than the dealer. It took an inordinate amount of time over two hours to address my issues and even then, it was not fully addressed because my remote which was "certified" for the car year in question could not be programmed. Moreover I sensed that the locksmith work load was back up and he did not want to spend more time trying to resolve the apparent issue. The key, using my own blank, cost $150.

On my return to LA, in exasperation, I began to look about for an entity to program my remote. I found one in Glendale, CA, JP Locksmith (Automotive Specialist). I spoke to the owner and we agreed on a price to program the remote. I said I would bring the car in next week. This gave me an opportunity to research other sources in the meantime. In our conversation, he mentioned that he was open until 8:00 PM. His Internet info. said he closed at 6:00 PM. I then called him back to double check his closing time. It was 8: o'clock. I then decided to brave the downtown LA peak hour traffic and drive to Glendale.

He immediately concluded that the battery in my new remote was probably defective. He pointed out an issue with my remote and decided to use a stock remote he had. It worked immediately. He tested it and had me test it, too. All done in 10 to 15 mins. I tried to negotiate his price but he would not budge because he had thrown in his own remote at no cost above the original quote.  Who can blame him for that.

The Key Cut Crew charges $114. for a $10 remote.

JP Locksmith used a common sense approach to pricing. The need for them  to make a living and the need for the customer to feel that pricing is commensurate with a garage hourly rate for specialist knowledge plus parts and, thus, what is reasonable for the job.

All I can say is that JP Locksmith did a remarkable job. They earned every penny they charged. How could I not give them a five star rating.</Review>

<username>Kyle Souza</username><time>1619647542596</time><Rate>2</Rate><Text>Very disappointing experience with BMW Vista service.  I had an 04 BMW that service was less than stellar at this shop and I thought I would give the Vista store another chance.  The shop is closer to me but the service is not what I expect.  I brought the car in for an oil change and brake fluid change.  There were 2 outstanding recalls on the car.  I did opt to have the recalls completed however I did not understand that comforts I was used to would be "deleted" from the car.  The recall was for the door latches and when that was completed, the electric/power opening feature of the car was removed.
The driver's side door handle does not operate properly but the door was able to open prior to the "power open" feature being removed.
I also wasn't made aware of bushings that needed replacement in the suspension but was made aware of the repair of $1200 for the door handle that isn't working properly.  Shouldn't safety be first?

The tech that performed the service on the car did not respect my vehicle.  Although it is an '06 750li, it should still be treated with care.  The tech must have played the radio for extended periods of time while working on the car as the battery came back almost completely discharged.  It was only at 30% and had been charged to 100% about 4 weeks prior to my service visit.  I could tell that at one point the tech must have had to jump the vehicle to start it as the protective cover from the positive terminal under the hood was removed and not replaced.

The tech must also be unfamiliar with how to service a BMW as when the door panels were removed from the car, the battery was not disconnected and now there is an airbag fault light in the car.

Due to one of the recalls, the programming was removed from the vehicle and the vehicle will have to be reprogrammed.  The windows no longer roll up with the key fob and the trunk no longer closes with the key fob either.  The shop foreman told me that this is not "factory programming" so it couldn't be returned to the car.  This is misinformation as the "loaner" car and another friend's BMW perform the roll up/closing action with the key fob.

The trunk also doesn't open as smoothly as it did prior to bringing it in for service.  The hood struts also appear to be weakened from having the hood open for an extended period of time.

I like not having to work on my own car however I'm not sure I have an alternative given the poor experience from BMW of Vista.

I also expect that my car doesn't receive scratches from getting serviced.

I love my older BMW but do not even like the service provided at BMW of Vista.<//Text>< pics>

< Review>
If it were not for the excellent service from Kassandra my Service Advisor, this would be a 1-star review. When I arrived, I parked and walked in past other service advisors and no greeting. No clear signage was present on where to form a line, so once the waiting customers backed up in the service area it seemed like no one cared about order of arrival, just whoever could run up to them the fastest. My wait time for scheduled maintenance was decent, but I decided to spend some of the time looking at the SUVs outside since we're considering trading in my car for something larger. I walked that lot a while, circling the X5s that they were offering specials on. Salesmen walked past me and not one asked if I needed help or wanted more information. However,  a man and his son who were also there for servicing walked out on the lot after me and a salesman RAN outside to catch up to them and ask them what they needed help with. Being six months pregnant and exhausted, I made my way back in the building and was greeted by another salesman who barely wanted to make eye contact and reluctantly asked me if I needed help. At that point, BMW of Vista had let me know that my payment for servicing was all that was welcome there. Even my courtesy wash was half-done, despite the influx of Auto Nation customers who came in for one at the same time as my appointment. I too, am an Auto Nation customer and purchased my BMW in Torrance, but I see the excellent experience I had when purchasing my vehicle from Auto Nation stopped there. I would have loved to let the manager know about my experience when I was there, but they were busy being serenaded by a guitarist (it must pay the cost to be the boss I guess), but to customers that kind of frivolity can only help explain why the sales team and majority of the service staff are lackluster and rude. Again, kudos to Kassandra for her kindness and excellent service, but I would be happy to drive the extra miles to get my car serviced at any other BMW dealership in any direction than to return to BMW of Vista, and I will never purchase a car here either.<//Review>

<user>109961135051044332075< /user><name>Albert Gedanken<//name><time>1619559608645< /time>< rating>
4<//rating>
< text>
The I3 nestled in 3KW of solar panels.

BMW Vista
Craig Mayville
Ryan Bowlan

My name is Gary Brown, and it is two weeks after the purchase of the 2017 I3 Rex, vin V891803.  I will present this review in 2 parts, the dealership and the car.

The Dealership:

I had already identified 2 examples of 3-year-old models with the Rex option in San Diego.  I set morning and afternoon appointments intending to buy one or the other.  BMW of Vista was the first and only visit that day.   The entire experience was just as I expected.  After all, any trip to a BMW dealer is kinda like mecca especially when you are buying your third bimmer.  I bought the brand many years ago so all that was left was the details.

The staff was easygoing, knowledgeable and this made the experience fun.  There were kinks and it ended up taking all day, but this is the beginning of a long relationship, so the investment was worth it.  There were only two missteps that deserve discussion.

I made the appointment to see an electric car and you showed me a depleted battery.  It gave me the opportunity to see the Rex in action but that is not what this car is about.  Besides, it is never good to leave any batteries completely discharged.

The second misstep is much more subtle and is as much my fault as yours.  This was the first time I have ever touched an electric car.  Sure, I did a bunch of research and became knowledgeable but reading about it is quite different than driving it.  I had a 150-mile journey over a pretty big mountain with few gas stations in the middle of the trip to get home and left the shop with half a battery and a 2-gal gas tank.

I needed to do planning that my E46 wagon or any car for that matter, never required.  In a perfect world, you should have talked with me about the ride home and I should have listened.  The great engineering BMW did save the day.  I was sad that I pulled into Pine Valley at the top of the mountain with 17 miles of range left but happy when I got to the bottom of the mountain and found 17 miles of additional electric range.

The Car:

This is the tightest vehicle I have ever driven.  Everything from the body and drive train to the buttons and knobs are tight.  Yesterday I moved the 325xi for the picture above and it is the first time in 6 years that the wagon felt old.  The engineering of the I3 is impeccable.

I live in the desert with no utilities and the single biggest factor is my ability to charge with sunlight.  I had to buy an industrial inverter but at the end of the day, the I3 fits right in.  The ability to change the charge level is a welcome feature allowing me to run the house normally with the car charging.  I traveled 35 miles to use the nearest public charger and the I3 performed flawlessly.  Now that I am home, charging is no longer an issue.

I have noticed that the indicated range of both the battery and rex are changing all the time and while this behavior is totally expected, it is disconcerting at first.   This morning I did the 8-mile post office trip, left with 119 miles electric range and got home with 133 miles indicated.  I have pondered how I would design the system differently but quickly concluded that the engineers did it right and I am already used to it after only a week.

In Conclusion:

I am in the autumn of my life and I wanted a taste of the future now.  This is the future.  I have reduced my carbon footprint to almost zero and have not only given up nothing but greatly improved the quality of my daily life.  The dealership experience was top notch and BMW really outdid themselves with this vehicle.  I look forward to a long and pleasant relationship with my I3.

I would do this whole thing again in a heartbeat.  Thank you all.</text>

<Text>I wish the dealer had been much clearer beforehand about the total price, and afterwards I wish they had provided much better information about the work that was done for the unexpectedly-high cost. Started out 5 stars, but ended 1 star ...
Enjoyable until it came to talking numbers ...
We were looking for something very specific and decided to evaluate the options at BMW Vista. We went in a later on a Friday evening; it was not busy, which was great. We started with a salesmen (Mo) who was accommodating and attentive at the time. We told him what we were in the market for - a used BMW M3 and an unknown business car for my wife. We drove the 2 different used M3s knowing they did not meet the exact colors and specs we wanted, but needed to do our due diligence. The salesmen was helpful even though we declined on those cars. We moved on to looking for a business/luxury vehicle. We drove a used m550i and X5, but they were not a good fit for my wife. We made an appointment with Mo for Sunday 10:30 to check out a brand new X5 and X6 that both had to be pulled from remote dealer car lots.

We arrived at the dealer on Sunday. We sat down and found out the cars requested were not moved for some paperwork issue that we were not told about (that raises an eyebrow). The salesmen then redirects us to look at brand new 5 series. We play along for a bit and drive the new car. Talking with the salesmen, being polite to say we rather look at the other vehicles we set an appointment for. We go on a ride from Vista to Encinitas to ‚Äúhunt down the cars.‚Äù  Time is ticking well passed lunch time. We tell the salesmen directly that we see through his sales tactics, and they are not going to work. We turn down the X5 and arrive at the X6 ... almost 3 hours after the scheduled appointment time. We tell the salesmen we appreciate his time and that this is the X6 is the closest thing on trim level to what we were looking for. Was very specific and did not say ‚Äúthis is the car‚Äù or ‚Äúlet‚Äôs buy it.‚Äù

We test drive back to Vista and immediately the salesmen wants to talk sale. We tell him again that we are doing our due diligence/research and would not be buying today. We said we would look at their finance and numbers. We say flat out that my wife doesn‚Äôt fit in the X6 (steering wheel does not move far enough) and the X6 is not red ... and it is not a car (it‚Äôs an SUV). He then starts with the comment of his time being valuable and he has spent a lot of time with us. Understood, we said we appreciated his time more than once and know he‚Äôs been hustling. However, if the salesmen valued our time then he would have called before the appointment to tell us the vehicles were not there. Instead he wanted to get us in the door to bide time. Also, if time were valuable, we would not have gone on a 3 hour hunt for cars when we specifically made an appointment. We do not enjoy our time being wasted either.

It then gets a bit more tense and salesmen asks ‚Äúwhat he can do to make a sale today.‚Äù The answer to him was ‚Äúnothing.‚Äù We stated flat out again that the sales tactics were not going to work. He got a bit defensive and said ‚Äúnothing is not going to feed my wife and kids.‚Äù At that very moment we saw the salesmen‚Äôs true motivations ... it was not the customer‚Äôs best interests. That comment, dripping with guilt and emotional manipulation by tugging at heart strings, is not what people come to a BMW dealer for. We know times are tough right now, but that is no excuse for pushy sales tactics and unprofessional comments when a salesmen is told ‚Äúno.‚Äù We are the customers and at the end of the day it is our money to spend, not the salesmen‚Äôs money; something every salesmen should remember.</Text>

<Text>My lease was to end in a few weeks.  I called to make an appointment to discuss the options for the lease end.  I met with Sal who guided me through what I could consider.  Having been a customer of BMW of Vista for a number of years, Sal, Corey, and Steve treated me very warmly.  After looking at my options and having the opportunity to test drive the class of BMW I was interested in, I gave Sal the details of what I was interested in.   He asked what I would like to see my lease payment to be and discussed it with sales manager.  He returned with a comparison of what the payment would typically be based on my down payment and what they were willing to do based on my loyalty to the dealership.  The lease agreement they proposed was perfect.  Sal had to pick the car up at a location off site.  When he returned it was discovered the car I had agreed on had been committed to another dealership.  The good news turned out to be that the car they would give me had several additional features, including upgraded paint among several other items.  The lease payment would remain the same.  When I met with Steve in the finance office the process was very efficient and cordial.  I was offered certain warranty additions which I declined.  In some cases that can be a moment when it becomes a bit of a "hard sell" to convince one that they should purchase some level of warranty upgrade.  Steve did none of that.  He simply presented the choices and accepted my decision without further "selling."  Sal did a great job of all the little details related to BMW Assist and setting up a handful of the technology matters that are engineered into a BMW.  I have had to take care of a few details related to my insurance, needing to send them documents regarding the lease, etc.  Sal and Steve's responses have been prompt.  I highly recommend the team at BMW of Vista.  They approach their business in a professional manner.  There is never a feeling of being "sold." BMW of Vista was extremely accommodating - when our car went into limp mode, they were close by and took us right in. Ramon was outstanding in his handling of our situation! My reason for not giving 5 stars was because of the price of the parts. Yes, I know "it's a BMW", but when I can get OEM parts online at 20% of the cost charged by the dealer, I have to complain a little. I can justify $20-25 for a spark plug, but $100? But again Ramon helped out here and we now have an 8 year old X5 that runs better than it has since we bought it 2 years ago.</text>

< text>
Although I wasn't expecting it, I had a fantastic experience at BMW of Vista. I went in to test drive a 540i to compare it to a Q70. Paul greeted me and quickly found a 540i on the lot. After a decent test drive, I didn't even want to check out the Q70. I said I was planning on selling my truck first but would be willing to entertain a trade-in offer. They quickly generated an offer that I thought was acceptable. Although I didn't mention it (didn't need to), we were on a short timetable and only had roughly 3 hours to spare at the dealer. Paul was very cognizant of our time and did not delay at all for things that were in his control. They brought me a fair offer on the 540i, to which I countered. The counter was accepted with a request to get a certificate from my bank's auto buying program. BMW of Vista showed their willingness to come to a price that worked for both of us. No pressure felt and no waiting games. We were in the dealership for about 3 1/2 hours total and drove out with our new 540i. I returned the next day (I ran out of time the day of the purchase) to be taught how to operate all the functions and controls. Paul happily had one of their 'smart guys' come out and teach us.< /text>

This was first time that I brought in my car to get services at BMW of Vista and  I was so impressed with their customer service.  Kathy is absolutely amazing!  The first time I went in she scheduled a recall on the air bags on my BMW.  She explained the process and the work that was to be completed and then she fixed me up with a loaner car.   The mechanics found some issues that did not pass safety tests and Kathy kept me informed with the concerns.  I had explained to her that I had purchased my car at Carmax and I had purchased an extended warranty with them.  She called to verify my deductible and I was happily told that the over $2500 bill would only cost me $300!   I scheduled another appointment and I was given a loaner car while they fixed the safety issues.  I appreciate the extra attention to details that you get at BMW of Vista!  I will no longer bring my car to anybody else for repairs.  The convenience of getting a loaner, the quality of work that is done, and the customer service is top notch.  Thank you BMW of Vista and to Kathy in the service department!  I will happily be a returning customer and I will definitely be purchasing my next car with you.</review>

Kyle at Finance Department was also pleasant to deal with.

Thank you Kyle & David Lopez!< /text>

<Text>Service Department Review:  theme is miss-communication and not following through.

Received a recall notice in the mail, it seemed serious as it referred to a potential fire that could spark and cause significant damage.  Called service department to drop off my car.  I talked was able to get an appt the next day (Friday) at 1pm, the rep mentioned that the repair would take 2-3 business days.  She also informed me that I would be able to have a loaner car without issue while the car was being repaired.

Arrive at 1pm.  At 1:15pm I was able to meet with Braie a service adviser. He was nice and seemed to listen to my feedback that I knew my car would have other potential repairs pop-up but that I would not be repairing anything other then the recall items for this visit.  I also talked to him about the communication I received about the 2-3 day quote on time for repair and that I would need a loaner car during that period especially since I was going out of town Fri night-Sun night. He said to be sure to let the loaner car manager know this when booking the car.

I was able to talk with the Loaner Vehicle Manager Miguel.  Miguel entered my info to set me up with a loaner vehicle.  I saw a notice on his desk that if the car was not returned by the next morning following the completion of repairs there would be a $99/day charge for the car.  I asked Miguel about this an explained that over the phone and in talking with Braie that the repair might take 2-3 days so I just wanted to be sure since I was going out of town for the weekend that there wouldn't be a chance that I would be charged additional fees for the loaner car.  Miguel stated that this recall repair would be quick, completed today (Friday), and the loaner would be due back Sat morning.  I tried to explain that this is different then what the first 2 people said but he stated "I'm the Loaner car manager, I think I know what I'm talking about" in a condescending tone.  I said "ok, well if that is the case is there any other option?"  He said that he could have a shuttle take me back home today and then pick me up at 7:30am on Monday to ensure I could get my car and make it to work.  Miguel said he would arrive at work at 6:45am Monday and asked me to call him to confirm the 7:30am pickup.  Sounded fine to me, the porter driver was ready quickly and took me home.  The porter driver was an excellent driver and was the most personable person I met at the dealership.  Luckily, even though the appointment was 15min late I was able to make my flight out of town for the weekend.

Monday morning at 7am I tried to call Miguel, no answer.  I then tried the main number, they asked who my service adviser was, I said Braie, they transferred me to him, he said the car wasn't ready, he said he'd look into the shuttle to get me, and then I assume I'd get a loaner and go to work.  10min later, no call back, so I call the main line again, transferred to Braie again, hung up on me.  Call back again and at this time I'm running out of time I tell the receptionist that I'll find my own way to work and check in later to see if the car will be done today (Monday).

Monday 8:57am, still never got a call back from Braie after he apparently hung up on me but did receive a vehicle report via email/text.  I reviewed the report, said "no" to additional items that I already said "no" to in our initial meeting.

Noon, no word from Braie so I emailed him to see if the car would be ready to pick up today.  1hr 25min later, he responded saying it was ready.
I called the main number to arrange for a shuttle pickup at 5pm from my work.  The person was nice and said sure we will be there at 5. As she almost hung up I asked her "don't you need my work address?"  She got and I thought all was good. 5:10, no pickup came. Called Miguel, he said he would fix it or get me himself. 10min later no call back, called main # again, took 2 tries, finally got picked up & got my car.

< Review>
Let me be clear with this review...this is the WORST service shop I've ever visited.  The sales department was outstanding when I bought my 750 in 2015 but the service department is absolutely 180 degrees different and horrible as of recently. When I bought my last BMW CPO and it needed work under the warranty in the first year, the experience was pleasant. Last year, my vehicle needed more work so I took it back to where I bought it and that was a huge mistake. My service advisor, Rachel, was horrible and obviously inept at customer service.  When I brought in my car, she was pleasant.  I agree with her on a $150 diagnostic fee to be paid if the work needed wasn't covered by my extended warranty.  When the diagnostic was completed and the insurance company agreed to pay only a portion of the repairs that they suggested were needed, she called me to suggest that I pay more than $8k for repairs.  I declined and told them to just perform the $2k worth of repairs that the insurance company agreed to pay. She became irate that I wouldn't pay out of pocket and tried to charge me more than $500 in diagnostic fees whereas the agreement was $150 if the insurance didn't pay for the repairs.  I told her firmly that was outside of what we agreed upon or what the estimate we signed stated. I instructed her to just do what the insurance paid for and I'd come get my car for a second opinion then she hung up on me. When I came to get my car, she acted as though she hadn't just rudely hung up on a customer. As I pulled out of the parking lot, my check engine light came on. Not wanting to deal with this dishonest shop again, I took my car to my regular mechanic shop and they checked it out and told me to take it back to BMW of Vista for the issue was most likely caused by the other  mechanic' s shotty work when replacing my spark plugs and was now causing  a misfire.  No matter where you buy your BMW or how you view dealerships versus private shops, AVOID this dealership at all COST. They are hacks that attempt to overcharge and become combative and grossly unprofessional  if you don't acquiesce.  Save yourself the stress and money and go to a reputable, honest, and professional establishment not this one. If this app allowed zero stars, this review would be most accurate.

Follow up:  After this review, the owner responded for the sake of saving face here. He offers that his GM would attempt to rectify the matter. Well, I received a call from the service manager a few days later in February and he said that he'd look into the matter and get back yet it's the end of March and haven't heard back from the guy yet.   We can agree respectfully that the only thing worse than bad service is "lip service".

If you care about your car and money, take the time and see the pattern of the other poor reviews and there is an obvious pattern.  The sales' experience is deliberate but the service experience is horrendous and rather unscrupulous.

Again, normally I don't waste my time reviewing bad organizations but in this case I must warn others before they trust their prized vehicles with this shop when there are so many better options in North County that you can trust.<//Review>

We originally found the car using the USAA car buying service, which was a huge help. I didn't feel pressured to buy at any point, Paul and Kyle (in finance) answered all of my questions and were extremely patient with me as we went through process. My husband wasn't able to be present at the transaction due to working in LA - so, BMW of Vista had me sign my end of the paperwork at the dealer, and that evening they DELIVERED my 328d to our home in Temecula, and brought the rest of the paperwork for my husband to sign at home. < review>
OVERVIEW
This isn't a review by someone who didn't get the deal they wanted or experienced "bad" sales customer service. I bought an $85,000 car from BMW and follows is a terrible account me being charged for a loaner car (during a service) that BMW had provided and then several months of broken promises to resolve the problem

_______________________________________________________________

5 Month update
BMW finally settled the issue. It ended up being a lot of extra work calling off the lawyer and the BBB but at least they did give me a refund - what a journey. The manager convinced me to give them another try for service. It ended up being an experience that wasn't horrible the second time around.

4 Month  Update
About 30 days ago I got a call from the general manager Mya Bradbury after I sent them an email outlining my troubles. He opened with "you have had one hell of an experience". Then like a knight in shining armor, he came in to save the day. Promising he would have this resolved and a payment out to me asap. I was relieved. Fast forward to today. No check, no return of phone calls or emails and when I finally got hold the sales manager, I was told I needed to take this up with the service director. I pleaded with Scott (the sales manager) explaining that Charles (the service director) and Mya (the general manager) already took responsibility of the issue and said would send me my $318, but have not fulfilled their promises. Why do I have to go back to square one? Please just do what you said you would do. He gave me another empty promise of a callback and put the phone down without taking my number. At this point, I have filed a complaint with the better business bureau. Let's see where it goes from here.

3-month update.
I've lost track of emails and phone calls at this point. Still dealing with this, like a ping pong ball between BMW and enterprise. BMW promised to send me a check 6 weeks ago to cover the cost of the rental. Still no check. When I called the service manager to discuss an update, he mysteriously decided that enterprise would refund me instead and decided not to send a check after all, all of course with no notification to me. Is anyone at BMW reading this? I bought an $85,000 car from BMW and this has been one of the worst run-around experiences I have ever been through.

Original review:
This would have been a 5-star review because BMW service is normally amazing. The reason it's getting a 1 star is that I took my X5 to this place for a service. Everything was normal, they gave me a loaner car while they were working on mine in June of 2017. I had to go to Enterprise because they didn't have a car for me. Enterprise took my credit card but I was assured that BMW would pay for it. Fast forward to October of 2017 and I see a charge for $318 on my credit card. Upon calling Enterprise I am told BMW hasn't paid its bills. Now I have to run around making several calls, waiting for callbacks and generally dealing with this headache to clear up this whole mess. Thanks alot BMW of Vista. My main worry now is that when dealers stop paying their bills it might be a sign of them going out of business......</review>

<Review>I bought a 328i here at BMW of Vista about a month ago, like a week before Thanksgiving of 2016.  Initially my brother and I were just stop by and see what they had to offer.  We had no intention to buy on that day.  We were talking to a couple of dealers in Orange County since they had good deals due to volume sale.  And so we were getting ready for Black Friday kind of deal the week after.

So one Saturday morning after a the exercise, we decided to check out BMW of Vista, ran into an very nice sale person Michael W.  He took us for a test drive and show us the feature of the car,etc...  After getting back to the dealer, he said let's go make a deal.  So we were just well we're already here and let's see what they offer.

The first offer were pretty nice but since we were already talking to other dealers we knew and had a specific number in mind and made the offer with ~ 21% off the MSRP and they said OK.  We were very surprised and agree to the deal.  It is the best deal I ever had.

Since we weren't ready so I had to call my wife to bring the $ and paper work to buy the care.  Through out the whole process Michael never pressure us to buy and he was very nice, calm and reasonable.  We made jokes and had good laugh, etc...  It is one of the best car buying experience I had.

Then a week later, my brother in-law saw the car and he asked.  I told him how much we paid for and he said, what.... are you kidding?  He could not believe it.  Next week his car broke down and he is looking for a new car.  He went and did test drive for Lexus, Audi.... Eventually he ask to see if he can test drive our car since he did not want to stop by the dealer just to save some time.  He did and liked it a lot.  He asked me to call the same sale person Michael W.  and wanted the same deal.

So I called Michael W. back and told him about it.  The only thing is he wanted a different color.  Michael W. spent a few days searching for the car.  We went back and forth a couple times since BMW of Vista had a similar car but a bit different and cost more.  Eventually, he found one but it was at a different dealer.  About three weeks after I bought my car, we agreed on the second deal and so Michael asked to call my brother to give him a credit card for the deposit so he can transfer the car to his dealer.  My brother immediately called Michael back and wait.  Fifteen minutes later Michael called back and said the car was no longer available from the other deal but he said he will sell my brother the other car that we talked about earlier in the week but did not went thru due to higher price with more discount.  I could not believe it.  The dealer wanted to keep their word and honor the deal.  They were kept their promise.
So the deal that my brother got was even better.  It is 22% off the MSRP.
He was so happy.  The next day he took the car to work and texted me to thank me for the deal.  I told him enjoy the car.

I don't know when I buy another BMW but the next time I am buying another BMW, I will definitely go the BMW of Vista.  I would buy from them again.

Anthony</Review>< Pictures>
